VALUES ('d2920000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001', 'Module 1: Historical and Current Common-Law Principles', 'Traces boundary law from English common law through American and Texas practice: how boundaries are created, the estates and interests recognized in land, the deeds that convey them, and the doctrines courts use to interpret descriptions.', 'intermediate', 3, 1, 'published', ARRAY['land-law','boundary-law','texas','nmsu-sur292']::text[], true, 'nmsu-sur292', true, 'approved', 180, 'intermediate')
ON CONFLICT (id) DO UPDATE SET title=EXCLUDED.title, description=EXCLUDED.description, order_index=EXCLUDED.order_index, status='published', is_academic=true, acc_course_id=EXCLUDED.acc_course_id, is_published=true, review_status='approved', tags=EXCLUDED.tags, estimated_hours=EXCLUDED.estimated_hours, updated_at=now();
VALUES ('d2920110-0000-0000-0000-000000000001', 'd2920000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001', 'Lesson 1: The Origins of Boundary Law', '', ARRAY['Boundary law is ancient; livery of seisin and beating the bounds show how transfer and boundary memory worked before reliable written deeds.','Three streams of law govern land: common (case) law under stare decisis, statute law, and equity.','Real property is governed by the lex loci - the law of the state where the land lies.','Boundaries determine the limits of rights, not the rights themselves; surveyors find facts (where), courts decide law (what).','Texas is a common-law state, but its titles flow from four sovereigns, not the U.S. federal government.']::text[], 1, 30, '[]'::jsonb, '[]'::jsonb, ARRAY['land-law','boundary-law','texas','nmsu-sur292']::text[], 'published', true, 'approved', true, NULL, ARRAY['Describe the historical and cultural roots of boundaries and boundary marking.','Explain how English common law became the foundation of American property law (lex loci).','Define the role of stare decisis and the difference between common law, statute law, and equity.']::text[]);
VALUES ('d2920110-0000-0000-0000-000000000002', 'd2920000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001', 'Lesson 2: How Boundaries Are Created', '', ARRAY['Boundaries are created three ways: by action (ground survey), by words (deed), and by law (statute/common).','A boundary created by words is as binding as one run on the ground.','A corner is a point (any end or change of direction); a monument is the physical witness at or near it.','A boundary is fixed forever at its original location, but a property line may change by agreement, estoppel, acquiescence, adverse possession, or judicial action.','Texas uses metes-and-bounds keyed to GLO survey + abstract number, not the PLSS township-range grid.']::text[], 2, 35, '[]'::jsonb, '[]'::jsonb, ARRAY['land-law','boundary-law','texas','nmsu-sur292']::text[], 'published', true, 'approved', true, NULL, ARRAY['Distinguish the three methods of creating a boundary: by action, by words, and by law.','Differentiate a corner from a monument and natural from artificial monuments.','Explain the original-survey rule and the doctrines that may later modify a property line.']::text[]);
VALUES ('d2920110-0000-0000-0000-000000000003', 'd2920000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001', 'Lesson 3: Estates and Interests in Land', '', ARRAY['Freehold estates (fee simple, fee tail, life estate) historically carried seisin; non-freehold estates are the leaseholds/tenancies.','Fee simple absolute is the greatest estate but still bows to eminent domain, escheat, police power, and taxation.','Fee simple determinable (''so long as'') reverts automatically (possibility of reverter); fee on condition subsequent (''but if'') requires the grantor to exercise a right of re-entry.','A reversion stays with the grantor; a remainder goes to a third party created by the same grant.','Texas presumes a conveyance passes the whole fee unless a lesser estate is expressly limited (Section 5.001).']::text[], 3, 35, '[]'::jsonb, '[]'::jsonb, ARRAY['land-law','boundary-law','texas','nmsu-sur292']::text[], 'published', true, 'approved', true, NULL, ARRAY['Differentiate freehold from non-freehold (leasehold) estates.','Define fee simple absolute, fee tail, life estate, and the defeasible fees, and identify the language that creates each.','Distinguish present interests from future interests (reversion vs. remainder) and apply the Texas presumption that a conveyance passes the whole estate.']::text[]);
VALUES ('d2920110-0000-0000-0000-000000000004', 'd2920000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001', 'Lesson 4: Title, Ownership, and Possession', '', ARRAY['Ownership is the bundle of rights; possession is custody/control; title is ownership plus the evidence of it.','Title is not the same as interest - a lienholder has interest but not title.','You can convey only the quantity and quality of interest you hold (own half, sell half).','Surveyors research the chain of title back to the original patent; attorneys may stop at a statutory number of years.','Color of title is an instrument that looks like it conveys title but, due to a defect, does not.']::text[], 4, 30, '[]'::jsonb, '[]'::jsonb, ARRAY['land-law','boundary-law','texas','nmsu-sur292']::text[], 'published', true, 'approved', true, NULL, ARRAY['Distinguish ownership, possession, and title, and separate title from mere interest.','Identify the sources of title and the chain of title a surveyor must research.','Define key interests and instruments: lien, lease, license, mortgage, deed of trust, escrow, and color of title.']::text[]);
VALUES ('d2920110-0000-0000-0000-000000000005', 'd2920000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001', 'Lesson 5: Deeds - Types, Covenants, and Requirements', '', ARRAY['Deeds differ by warranty: general warranty (all defects) > special warranty (grantor''s ownership period) > quitclaim (no warranty).','A grant deed passes after-acquired title automatically and implies statutory covenants.','Required elements: competent parties, written form, sufficient description, delivery (turns on intent), and acceptance.','NOT required for validity: consideration (generally), a date, witnesses, or notarial acknowledgment; recordation is not required for validity.','Texas: warranty comes from express ''warrant and forever defend'' language; ''grant'' implies only no-prior-conveyance and no-encumbrances (no covenant of seisin).']::text[], 5, 35, '[]'::jsonb, '[]'::jsonb, ARRAY['land-law','boundary-law','texas','nmsu-sur292']::text[], 'published', true, 'approved', true, NULL, ARRAY['Identify the principal types of deeds and the warranty each provides.','List the required elements of a valid deed and the elements that are not required.','Recognize the standard clauses of a deed (recitals, granting clause, habendum, reservations, exceptions) and apply Texas deed-warranty rules.']::text[]);

-- ===== Module 2: Module 2: Sources of Laws and Related Presumptions =====
