VALUES ('d2920000-0000-0000-0000-000000000002', 'Module 2: Sources of Laws and Related Presumptions', 'Examines the sources and hierarchy of American law, the structure of the federal and Texas court systems, how appellate cases become binding precedent, and the legal presumptions and inferences a surveyor relies on in boundary and title work — made Texas-specific throughout.', 'intermediate', 3, 2, 'published', ARRAY['land-law','boundary-law','texas','nmsu-sur292']::text[], true, 'nmsu-sur292', true, 'approved', 180, 'intermediate')
ON CONFLICT (id) DO UPDATE SET title=EXCLUDED.title, description=EXCLUDED.description, order_index=EXCLUDED.order_index, status='published', is_academic=true, acc_course_id=EXCLUDED.acc_course_id, is_published=true, review_status='approved', tags=EXCLUDED.tags, estimated_hours=EXCLUDED.estimated_hours, updated_at=now();
VALUES ('d2920210-0000-0000-0000-000000000001', 'd2920000-0000-0000-0000-000000000002', 'Sources and Hierarchy of Law', '', ARRAY['Law has a hierarchy: constitution > statute > administrative rule > ordinance, with common/case law filling the gaps and interpreting the rest.','Supremacy resolves conflicts in favor of the higher source; federal over state.','Boundary jurisdiction follows title: federal law for never-patented land, state law once patented.','Sovereign immunity bars common-law boundary remedies (adverse possession, acquiescence) against the government.','Texas surveyors mainly work in the Property Code, Natural Resources Code, Civ. Prac. & Rem. Code Ch. 16, and Occupations Code Ch. 1071, with TBPELS rules in 22 TAC Ch. 138.']::text[], 1, 30, '[]'::jsonb, '[]'::jsonb, ARRAY['land-law','boundary-law','texas','nmsu-sur292']::text[], 'published', true, 'approved', true, NULL, ARRAY['Name the principal sources of American law and rank them in order of authority.','Explain the doctrine of supremacy and how federal and state jurisdiction divide for boundary disputes.','Identify the Texas codes most relevant to surveying.']::text[]);
VALUES ('d2920210-0000-0000-0000-000000000002', 'd2920000-0000-0000-0000-000000000002', 'The Federal and Texas Court Systems', '', ARRAY['Courts run in three tiers: trial (finds facts), appellate (reviews law/procedure only), and supreme (discretionary final review).','Federal: U.S. District Courts -> 13 Courts of Appeals circuits -> U.S. Supreme Court.','Texas boundary/title suits begin in District Court (general jurisdiction).','Texas uniquely has TWO highest courts: the Supreme Court of Texas (civil — controls boundary law) and the Court of Criminal Appeals (criminal).','Texas now has effectively 15 courts of appeals (14 regional + the statewide Fifteenth), but private boundary appeals still go to the regional court.']::text[], 2, 35, '[]'::jsonb, '[]'::jsonb, ARRAY['land-law','boundary-law','texas','nmsu-sur292']::text[], 'published', true, 'approved', true, NULL, ARRAY['Describe the three tiers of courts (trial, appellate, supreme) and what each does.','Contrast the federal court structure with the Texas court structure.','Explain why Texas uniquely has two highest courts and which one decides boundary cases.']::text[]);
VALUES ('d2920210-0000-0000-0000-000000000003', 'd2920000-0000-0000-0000-000000000002', 'How a Case Becomes Law: Precedent and Legal Research', '', ARRAY['A trial ruling binds only its own case; an appellate opinion binds all courts in its jurisdiction and becomes precedent.','Stare decisis makes higher-court decisions binding (mandatory) and other decisions merely persuasive.','Only appellate opinions are reported; trial-court decisions are not published as precedent.','Primary sources state the law (cases, statutes, agency rules); secondary sources (treatises like Brown, encyclopedias, law reviews) explain it and cite to it.','Texas appellate opinions are published in the South Western Reporter; a citation gives parties, volume, reporter, page, court, and year.']::text[], 3, 30, '[]'::jsonb, '[]'::jsonb, ARRAY['land-law','boundary-law','texas','nmsu-sur292']::text[], 'published', true, 'approved', true, NULL, ARRAY['Trace the path by which a trial decision becomes binding appellate precedent.','Distinguish binding precedent from persuasive (advisory) authority and stare decisis.','Use the basic tools of legal research — primary vs. secondary sources, reporters, and case citations.']::text[]);
VALUES ('d2920210-0000-0000-0000-000000000004', 'd2920000-0000-0000-0000-000000000002', 'Recording Acts, Notice, and the Bona Fide Purchaser', '', ARRAY['Recording acts replace common-law ''first in time'' with a public-record system keyed to notice.','Notice can be actual (real knowledge) or constructive (the record, or open possession).','Texas is a PURE NOTICE state: a BFP without notice wins even if the prior grantee records first or the BFP never records (Prop. Code §§13.001–13.002).','A bona fide purchaser needs valuable consideration, good faith, and no notice; record in the county where the land lies.','Madison v. Gordon: possession is constructive notice only if ''visible, open, exclusive, and unequivocal'' — a stricter Texas test; quitclaim grantees are generally not BFPs.']::text[], 4, 30, '[]'::jsonb, '[]'::jsonb, ARRAY['land-law','boundary-law','texas','nmsu-sur292']::text[], 'published', true, 'approved', true, NULL, ARRAY['Explain the purpose of recording acts and the difference between actual and constructive notice.','Classify Texas as a pure notice jurisdiction and apply Property Code §§13.001–13.002.','State the elements of the bona fide purchaser doctrine and how possession can defeat it.']::text[]);
VALUES ('d2920210-0000-0000-0000-000000000005', 'd2920000-0000-0000-0000-000000000002', 'Presumptions and Inferences in Boundary Law', '', ARRAY['A presumption is a conclusion the law directs from established facts; it is not evidence but can substitute for it when evidence is missing.','Conclusive presumptions are absolute; rebuttable presumptions (most boundary rules) yield to superior evidence.','An inference is a fact-deduction reasoned by the factfinder — not a presumption imposed by law.','Surveys, field notes, corners, and ancient surveys carry strong presumptions of correctness; land abutting a road/non-navigable stream is presumed to run to the center.','The Texas dignity of calls (natural > artificial > course > distance > quantity) is a rebuttable rule of construction subordinate to grant intent and the original surveyor''s footsteps.']::text[], 5, 30, '[]'::jsonb, '[]'::jsonb, ARRAY['land-law','boundary-law','texas','nmsu-sur292']::text[], 'published', true, 'approved', true, NULL, ARRAY['Define a legal presumption and distinguish conclusive from rebuttable presumptions.','Distinguish a presumption from an inference and from evidence.','Apply common surveying presumptions and Texas boundary presumptions to retracement problems.']::text[]);

-- ===== Module 3: Module 3: Legal Doctrines / Principles in Property Law =====
