VALUES ('d2920000-0000-0000-0000-000000000003', 'Module 3: Legal Doctrines / Principles in Property Law', 'Easements and related non-possessory property interests, the methods by which they are created and terminated, and the Texas-specific rules governing adverse possession, encroachments, licenses, covenants, and dedication. Emphasizes how Texas disfavors prescriptive easements and channels access disputes into express grants and easements by necessity.', 'intermediate', 3.5, 3, 'published', ARRAY['land-law','boundary-law','texas','nmsu-sur292']::text[], true, 'nmsu-sur292', true, 'approved', 210, 'intermediate')
ON CONFLICT (id) DO UPDATE SET title=EXCLUDED.title, description=EXCLUDED.description, order_index=EXCLUDED.order_index, status='published', is_academic=true, acc_course_id=EXCLUDED.acc_course_id, is_published=true, review_status='approved', tags=EXCLUDED.tags, estimated_hours=EXCLUDED.estimated_hours, updated_at=now();
VALUES ('d2920310-0000-0000-0000-000000000001', 'd2920000-0000-0000-0000-000000000003', 'What Is an Easement? Definition, Estates, and Classifications', '', ARRAY['An easement is a non-possessory right to use another''s land; fee title stays with the servient owner.','Appurtenant easements benefit a dominant estate and run with the land; easements in gross (utilities, pipelines) benefit a person/entity with no dominant estate.','Every easement involves three descriptions: dominant parcel, servient parcel, and the easement strip itself.','Affirmative easements permit an act; negative easements prevent a servient use and are narrowly recognized.']::text[], 1, 35, '[]'::jsonb, '[]'::jsonb, ARRAY['land-law','boundary-law','texas','nmsu-sur292']::text[], 'published', true, 'approved', true, NULL, ARRAY['State the legal definition of an easement and explain why it is a non-possessory interest.','Distinguish appurtenant easements from easements in gross and identify the dominant and servient estates.','Classify easements as affirmative or negative and identify common surveying easement types.']::text[]);
VALUES ('d2920310-0000-0000-0000-000000000002', 'd2920000-0000-0000-0000-000000000003', 'Creating Easements I: Express Grants, Reservations, and Estoppel', '', ARRAY['Easements are interests in land governed by the Statute of Frauds; they arise through writings or by operation of law.','The express, recorded easement is the most common and most-favored method — especially important in Texas, which disfavors implied/prescriptive easements.','A reservation creates a new interest kept by the grantor; an exception merely withholds something that already existed.','Easement by estoppel bars a landowner from denying an easement after inducing another''s reasonable, detrimental reliance.']::text[], 2, 30, '[]'::jsonb, '[]'::jsonb, ARRAY['land-law','boundary-law','texas','nmsu-sur292']::text[], 'published', true, 'approved', true, NULL, ARRAY['Explain why easements fall under the Statute of Frauds and how express easements are created.','Distinguish an exception from a reservation in a deed.','Describe easement by estoppel and its elements.']::text[]);
VALUES ('d2920310-0000-0000-0000-000000000003', 'd2920000-0000-0000-0000-000000000003', 'Creating Easements II: Implied, Necessity, Prescription, and Dedication', '', ARRAY['Implied-by-prior-use needs unity of ownership, open/apparent + continuous use, and reasonable necessity; after Hamrick v. Ward, landlocked road access must go through necessity, not prior use.','Easement by necessity in Texas requires unity of ownership before severance, strict (not mere) necessity, and necessity at severance — and it ends when the necessity ends.','Texas disfavors prescriptive easements; the exclusivity element means joint/shared use defeats the claim (Tran v. Macha).','Statutory dedication is by recorded plat; common-law dedication needs donative intent, reliance, and acceptance. Texas abolished implied dedication of public roads in small counties (Transp. Code Ch. 281, 1981).']::text[], 3, 40, '[]'::jsonb, '[]'::jsonb, ARRAY['land-law','boundary-law','texas','nmsu-sur292']::text[], 'published', true, 'approved', true, NULL, ARRAY['Distinguish implied easements by prior use from easements by necessity and state their Texas elements.','Explain the elements of a prescriptive easement and why Texas disfavors them.','Differentiate statutory from common-law dedication and explain the Texas 1981 limitation on implied dedication.']::text[]);
VALUES ('d2920310-0000-0000-0000-000000000004', 'd2920000-0000-0000-0000-000000000003', 'Adverse Possession: Elements and the Texas Statutory Scheme', '', ARRAY['Common-law adverse possession requires actual, open & notorious, exclusive, hostile, and continuous possession for the statutory period; permissive use is never hostile.','Texas adverse possession is wholly statutory (Civ. Prac. & Rem. Code Ch. 16) with multiple tracks: 3 yr (color of title), 5 yr (deed + taxes + use), 10 yr (use; 160-acre cap), 25 yr (recorded-but-void instrument).','The stronger the paper/title basis, the shorter the period; the 5-year tax-payment requirement and 10-year acreage cap are distinctively Texan.','Acquiescence (mutual mistake, no hostility) can move a boundary line silently — contrast with hostile adverse possession.']::text[], 4, 40, '[]'::jsonb, '[]'::jsonb, ARRAY['land-law','boundary-law','texas','nmsu-sur292']::text[], 'published', true, 'approved', true, NULL, ARRAY['List and explain the common-law elements of adverse possession.','Apply the Texas statutory limitation periods (§§16.024, 16.025, 16.026, 16.028) and their distinct requirements.','Explain color of title, tacking, and why Texas''s tax-payment and acreage-cap rules are distinctive.']::text[]);
VALUES ('d2920310-0000-0000-0000-000000000005', 'd2920000-0000-0000-0000-000000000003', 'Related Concepts: Licenses, Encroachments, Covenants, Eminent Domain, and Reversion', '', ARRAY['A license is revocable personal permission and creates no interest in land; an easement is an interest in land that (if appurtenant) runs with the land.','Encroachments are remedied in Texas by trespass-to-try-title/quiet title, injunction, or damages; there is no general innocent-improver statute, and the surveyed boundary usually controls.','Covenants restrict how the burdened owner may use his own land; easements grant another a right to use it.','Eminent-domain takings usually acquire only an easement unless the fee is necessary; vacated-street reversion runs to the centerline (radial on curves, angle-bisected at corners) and cannot exceed original boundaries.']::text[], 5, 35, '[]'::jsonb, '[]'::jsonb, ARRAY['land-law','boundary-law','texas','nmsu-sur292']::text[], 'published', true, 'approved', true, NULL, ARRAY['Compare and contrast a license with an easement.','Describe encroachments and the Texas remedies for them.','Distinguish covenants/restrictions from easements and explain reversion (reversionary) rights along vacated streets.']::text[]);
  'd2920350-0000-0000-0000-000000000001', 'Years remaining to perfect adverse possession (10-year statute)', 'Years remaining to perfect adverse possession (10-year statute)', 'Property Law — Doctrines', 'Adverse Possession', 'numeric_input', 'easy', 'A claimant began peaceable, adverse, and continuous possession of an unenclosed Texas tract in {{startYear}}, using it without any deed or tax payments. Proceeding under the 10-year statute (Tex. Civ. Prac. & Rem. Code §16.026), in what calendar year will the limitation period be satisfied so the claim can be perfected?', 'startYear + 10', '{"decimals":0,"unit":"","tolerance":0}', '[{"name":"startYear","type":"integer","min":1995,"max":2015}]'::jsonb, '[]'::jsonb, '[{"step_number":1,"title":"Identify the statutory period","calculation_template":"§16.026 requires 10 years of peaceable, adverse possession (no deed/taxes needed; 160-acre cap)."},{"step_number":2,"title":"Add the period to the start year","result_template":"{{startYear}} + 10 = {{_answer}}"}]'::jsonb, '{"method":"none"}'::jsonb, 'Under §16.026, ten years of continuous adverse possession are required. Beginning in {{startYear}}, the period is satisfied in {{_answer}}. (If the tract were larger than 160 acres, the claim would be capped unless enclosed or held under a recorded deed fixing the boundaries.)', 'd2920000-0000-0000-0000-000000000003', ARRAY['land-law','boundary-law','texas','nmsu-sur292','practice']::text[], true, 'seed:nmsu-sur292');
  'd2920350-0000-0000-0000-000000000002', 'Area of a strip easement (length × width)', 'Area of a strip easement (length × width)', 'Property Law — Doctrines', 'Easements', 'numeric_input', 'easy', 'A utility easement runs as a uniform strip {{width}} ft wide along a property line for a length of {{length}} ft. What is the area of the easement, in square feet?', 'width * length', '{"decimals":2,"unit":"sq ft","tolerance":0.5}', '[{"name":"width","type":"integer","min":10,"max":30},{"name":"length","type":"float","min":150,"max":600,"decimals":2}]'::jsonb, '[]'::jsonb, '[{"step_number":1,"title":"Strip area formula","formula":"A = width × length"},{"step_number":2,"title":"Substitute","result_template":"{{width}} × {{length:f2}} = {{_answer}} sq ft"}]'::jsonb, '{"method":"none"}'::jsonb, 'A uniform strip easement is a rectangle, so its area is simply width × length = {{width}} × {{length:f2}} = {{_answer}} sq ft.', 'd2920000-0000-0000-0000-000000000003', ARRAY['land-law','boundary-law','texas','nmsu-sur292','practice']::text[], true, 'seed:nmsu-sur292');
  'd2920350-0000-0000-0000-000000000003', 'Strip easement area converted to acres', 'Strip easement area converted to acres', 'Property Law — Doctrines', 'Easements', 'numeric_input', 'medium', 'A pipeline easement is a uniform strip {{width}} ft wide and {{length}} ft long. Express the easement area in acres (1 acre = 43,560 sq ft).', '(width * length) / 43560', '{"decimals":3,"unit":"ac","tolerance":0.005}', '[{"name":"width","type":"integer","min":20,"max":50},{"name":"length","type":"float","min":1000,"max":5000,"decimals":2}]'::jsonb, '[{"name":"areaSqFt","formula":"width * length"}]'::jsonb, '[{"step_number":1,"title":"Strip area in sq ft","formula":"A = width × length","calculation_template":"{{width}} × {{length:f2}} = {{areaSqFt:f2}} sq ft"},{"step_number":2,"title":"Convert to acres","calculation_template":"{{areaSqFt:f2}} ÷ 43,560"},{"step_number":3,"title":"Result","result_template":"= {{_answer}} ac"}]'::jsonb, '{"method":"none"}'::jsonb, 'Compute the rectangular strip area ({{width}} × {{length:f2}} = {{areaSqFt:f2}} sq ft), then divide by 43,560 sq ft/acre to get {{_answer}} acres.', 'd2920000-0000-0000-0000-000000000003', ARRAY['land-law','boundary-law','texas','nmsu-sur292','practice']::text[], true, 'seed:nmsu-sur292');

