VALUES ('d2920000-0000-0000-0000-000000000004', 'Module 4: Locating Sequential Conveyances', 'How surveyors and courts locate boundaries created one conveyance after another over time, applying senior/junior rights, the dignity (priority) of conflicting calls, and the rule that the original surveyor''s footsteps and the parties'' intent control.', 'intermediate', 4, 4, 'published', ARRAY['land-law','boundary-law','texas','nmsu-sur292']::text[], true, 'nmsu-sur292', true, 'approved', 240, 'intermediate')
ON CONFLICT (id) DO UPDATE SET title=EXCLUDED.title, description=EXCLUDED.description, order_index=EXCLUDED.order_index, status='published', is_academic=true, acc_course_id=EXCLUDED.acc_course_id, is_published=true, review_status='approved', tags=EXCLUDED.tags, estimated_hours=EXCLUDED.estimated_hours, updated_at=now();
VALUES ('d2920410-0000-0000-0000-000000000001', 'd2920000-0000-0000-0000-000000000004', 'Resolving Conflicts in Deeds: The Three Basic Elements', '', ARRAY['Courts resolve deed conflicts with three elements, in order: unwritten/possession rights, senior rights, then written intent.','A surveyor may apply senior rights and written intent but may NOT decide unwritten/possession rights — that is for a court.','The footsteps of the original surveyor, where identifiable, control over later ''more accurate'' measurements.','Stafford v. King (1867) is the seminal Texas case for both the footsteps rule and the dignity of calls.']::text[], 1, 30, '[]'::jsonb, '[]'::jsonb, ARRAY['land-law','boundary-law','texas','nmsu-sur292']::text[], 'published', true, 'approved', true, NULL, ARRAY['State the three elements courts use to resolve deed conflicts and rank them.','Explain which of those elements a surveyor may and may not apply.','Describe the surveyor''s duty to follow the footsteps of the original surveyor.']::text[]);
VALUES ('d2920410-0000-0000-0000-000000000002', 'd2920000-0000-0000-0000-000000000004', 'Sequential vs. Simultaneous Conveyances', '', ARRAY['Sequential = parcels carved out over time → senior/junior rights govern; junior absorbs excess/deficiency.','Simultaneous = subdivision lots created at one instant → no seniority; excess/deficiency apportioned proportionately.','Overlaps go to the senior parcel; gaps go to the seller (possibly the State).','A title search to the original conveyance is required because a ''simultaneous'' lot can carry a hidden senior right.','In Texas, proportioning is a genuine fallback behind original-survey footsteps.']::text[], 2, 30, '[]'::jsonb, '[]'::jsonb, ARRAY['land-law','boundary-law','texas','nmsu-sur292']::text[], 'published', true, 'approved', true, NULL, ARRAY['Define sequential and simultaneous conveyances and give an example of each.','Explain who gets overlaps and gaps under each scheme.','Apply senior rights to sequential conveyances and apportionment to simultaneous conveyances.']::text[]);
VALUES ('d2920410-0000-0000-0000-000000000003', 'd2920000-0000-0000-0000-000000000004', 'Senior and Junior Rights in Practice', '', ARRAY['A grantor cannot resell rights already conveyed; the junior deed takes only the remainder.','Excess or deficiency falls entirely on the junior parcel, not prorated with the senior.','Abutter calls are normally senior but are not a conclusive test — search title to the original conveyance.','Ambiguities in state patents are resolved for the State (patents are quitclaim, no warranty) — the reverse of private deeds.','A reservation, and any public grant to a private party, is construed in favor of the grantor.']::text[], 3, 30, '[]'::jsonb, '[]'::jsonb, ARRAY['land-law','boundary-law','texas','nmsu-sur292']::text[], 'published', true, 'approved', true, NULL, ARRAY['Explain the principle underlying senior rights and how a junior deed is cut back.','Evaluate when a call for an adjoiner reliably indicates seniority.','Describe how ambiguities in state patents are construed.']::text[]);
VALUES ('d2920410-0000-0000-0000-000000000004', 'd2920000-0000-0000-0000-000000000004', 'The Dignity (Priority) of Conflicting Calls', '', ARRAY['Order of dignity: senior/unwritten rights > natural monuments > artificial monuments > adjoiners > course > distance > area > coordinates.','The hierarchy reflects the least-likely-mistake principle and is rebuttable, not absolute.','A monument must be called for, identifiable, and undisturbed to control.','Intent and the original surveyor''s footsteps override the mechanical ranking — a call defeating intent is rejected regardless of its dignity.','Area/quantity and coordinates are the weakest elements.']::text[], 4, 35, '[]'::jsonb, '[]'::jsonb, ARRAY['land-law','boundary-law','texas','nmsu-sur292']::text[], 'published', true, 'approved', true, NULL, ARRAY['List the order of importance for conflicting boundary elements.','Distinguish natural monuments, artificial monuments, and adjoiner calls.','Explain how intent and the footsteps doctrine can override the mechanical hierarchy.']::text[]);
VALUES ('d2920410-0000-0000-0000-000000000005', 'd2920000-0000-0000-0000-000000000004', 'Reading the Words: Rules of Construction, Parol Evidence, and Errors', '', ARRAY['Construe the whole instrument to give effect to every term; particular descriptions control general ones; the earliest of equal rights is preferred.','''To'' is a word of exclusion — the call after ''to'' controls; a called monument controls, and its bearing/distance become controlling only if the monument is lost.','Parol evidence may explain an ambiguous PoB, show where a line was run, or show fraud — but may not add, subtract, or vary deed terms.','A plat the parties acted upon becomes part of the description; an erroneous or unrelied-upon plat is surplusage.','An isolable error is placed where it occurs; words control over conflicting figures; the first-stated factor is preferred when nothing else decides.']::text[], 5, 30, '[]'::jsonb, '[]'::jsonb, ARRAY['land-law','boundary-law','texas','nmsu-sur292']::text[], 'published', true, 'approved', true, NULL, ARRAY['Apply the principal rules of construction and maxims of jurisprudence to a deed.','State when parol evidence may and may not be used.','Locate and place an isolable error within a description.']::text[]);
VALUES ('d2920410-0000-0000-0000-000000000006', 'd2920000-0000-0000-0000-000000000004', 'Possession as Evidence and the Surveyor''s Responsibility', '', ARRAY['Lines of occupation can ripen into the ownership boundary through adverse possession, acquiescence, estoppel, or agreement.','Where the boundary is = question of fact (surveyor); what the boundary is = question of law (court).','A surveyor must disclose record-vs-occupation conflicts, not silently adopt the occupation line; otherwise liability and unmarketable title result.','Significance of a fence/record difference is judged by a reasonableness standard tied to scale and context.','A surveyor cannot reform a deed; a written boundary agreement among adjoiners turns occupation lines into record lines.']::text[], 6, 25, '[]'::jsonb, '[]'::jsonb, ARRAY['land-law','boundary-law','texas','nmsu-sur292']::text[], 'published', true, 'approved', true, NULL, ARRAY['Explain how lines of possession relate to record boundaries.','State the limits of a surveyor''s authority regarding unwritten rights.','Describe the surveyor''s disclosure duty when occupation and record differ.']::text[]);
  'd2920450-0000-0000-0000-000000000001', 'Junior remainder after senior call is satisfied', 'Junior remainder after senior call is satisfied', 'Boundary Law — Conveyances', 'Senior/Junior Rights', 'numeric_input', 'medium', 'Grantor O owns a tract with {{rec:f2}} ft of record frontage along a road. O first deeds the senior parcel, a width of {{senior:f2}} ft, to A. O then deeds ''the remainder'' to junior grantee B. A resurvey between the two controlling end monuments finds the true frontage is {{meas:f2}} ft. Applying senior rights (no proration), what frontage (ft) does junior parcel B receive?', 'meas-senior', '{"decimals":2,"unit":"ft","tolerance":0.05}', '[{"name":"rec","type":"float","min":300,"max":500,"decimals":2},{"name":"senior","type":"float","min":120,"max":220,"decimals":2},{"name":"defc","type":"float","min":-12,"max":12,"decimals":2}]'::jsonb, '[{"name":"meas","formula":"rec+defc"}]'::jsonb, '[{"step_number":1,"title":"Senior takes full width","calculation_template":"Senior A = {{senior:f2}} ft (unchanged)"},{"step_number":2,"title":"Measured total frontage","calculation_template":"{{rec:f2}} + ({{defc:f2}}) = {{meas:f2}} ft"},{"step_number":3,"title":"Junior remainder","result_template":"{{meas:f2}} − {{senior:f2}} = {{_answer}} ft"}]'::jsonb, '{"method":"none"}'::jsonb, 'Senior rights govern a sequential conveyance: A keeps its full {{senior:f2}} ft, and the junior B absorbs the entire excess/deficiency, taking the remainder = {{meas:f2}} − {{senior:f2}} = {{_answer}} ft.', 'd2920000-0000-0000-0000-000000000004', ARRAY['land-law','boundary-law','texas','nmsu-sur292','practice']::text[], true, 'seed:nmsu-sur292');
  'd2920450-0000-0000-0000-000000000002', 'Corrected distance when a monument controls over record distance', 'Corrected distance when a monument controls over record distance', 'Boundary Law — Conveyances', 'Dignity of Calls', 'numeric_input', 'medium', 'A line is described as bearing {{brg:dms}} for a record distance of {{rec:f2}} ft ''to a found {{mon}} monument.'' The monument is called for, identifiable, and undisturbed; it is found along the same bearing at a measured horizontal distance of {{meas:f2}} ft. Treating the monument as the controlling call, what corrected distance (ft) reaches the corner, and by how much does it exceed the record? Report the corrected distance.', 'meas', '{"decimals":2,"unit":"ft","tolerance":0.05}', '[{"name":"brg","type":"bearing"},{"name":"mon","type":"choice","choices":["iron pipe","concrete monument","stone"]},{"name":"rec","type":"float","min":120,"max":400,"decimals":2},{"name":"err","type":"float","min":-6,"max":8,"decimals":2}]'::jsonb, '[{"name":"meas","formula":"rec+err"}]'::jsonb, '[{"step_number":1,"title":"Identify the controlling call","calculation_template":"Called, identifiable, undisturbed {{mon}} > record distance"},{"step_number":2,"title":"Adopt the measured distance to the monument","result_template":"Corrected distance = {{meas:f2}} ft (record {{rec:f2}} ft is informative)"}]'::jsonb, '{"method":"none"}'::jsonb, 'An artificial monument that is called for, identifiable, and undisturbed controls over a conflicting distance. The corrected distance is the measured distance to the monument, {{meas:f2}} ft; the record {{rec:f2}} ft becomes controlling only if the monument is lost.', 'd2920000-0000-0000-0000-000000000004', ARRAY['land-law','boundary-law','texas','nmsu-sur292','practice']::text[], true, 'seed:nmsu-sur292');
  'd2920450-0000-0000-0000-000000000003', 'Gap or overlap width between two adjoining deeds', 'Gap or overlap width between two adjoining deeds', 'Boundary Law — Conveyances', 'Gaps and Overlaps', 'numeric_input', 'medium', 'A senior deed describes a parcel whose east line is at station {{e1:f2}} ft east of a common origin. The adjoining junior deed describes its west line at station {{w2:f2}} ft east of the same origin. Compute the width (ft) of the gap or overlap between the two deed lines (report a positive number for the magnitude).', 'abs(w2-e1)', '{"decimals":2,"unit":"ft","tolerance":0.05}', '[{"name":"e1","type":"float","min":200,"max":300,"decimals":2},{"name":"d","type":"float","min":-6,"max":6,"decimals":2}]'::jsonb, '[{"name":"w2","formula":"e1+d"}]'::jsonb, '[{"step_number":1,"title":"Locate the two deed lines","calculation_template":"Senior east line at {{e1:f2}} ft; junior west line at {{w2:f2}} ft"},{"step_number":2,"title":"Difference of stations","calculation_template":"{{w2:f2}} − {{e1:f2}} = {{d:f2}} ft"},{"step_number":3,"title":"Width magnitude","result_template":"|{{d:f2}}| = {{_answer}} ft (positive station diff = gap; negative = overlap)"}]'::jsonb, '{"method":"none"}'::jsonb, 'If the junior west line lies east of the senior east line, the strip between them is a gap (belongs to the seller/State); if it lies west, the deeds overlap (the overlap belongs to the senior). The width is the absolute difference of the two stations = {{_answer}} ft.', 'd2920000-0000-0000-0000-000000000004', ARRAY['land-law','boundary-law','texas','nmsu-sur292','practice']::text[], true, 'seed:nmsu-sur292');
  'd2920450-0000-0000-0000-000000000004', 'Bearing-distance to a corrected corner position (departure and latitude)', 'Bearing-distance to a corrected corner position (departure and latitude)', 'Boundary Law — Conveyances', 'Coordinate Computation', 'numeric_input', 'hard', 'From a found controlling corner at coordinates (N {{n0:f2}}, E {{e0:f2}}), a deed line runs {{brg:dms}} (a bearing of {{az:f2}} degrees from north, in the NE quadrant) for the corrected distance of {{dist:f2}} ft to the next corner. Compute the EASTING (E) of the next corner.', 'e0 + dist*sin(toRad(az))', '{"decimals":2,"unit":"ft","tolerance":0.05}', '[{"name":"n0","type":"float","min":4000,"max":6000,"decimals":2},{"name":"e0","type":"float","min":4000,"max":6000,"decimals":2},{"name":"az","type":"float","min":15,"max":75,"decimals":2},{"name":"dist","type":"float","min":150,"max":450,"decimals":2}]'::jsonb, '[{"name":"dep","formula":"dist*sin(toRad(az))"}]'::jsonb, '[{"step_number":1,"title":"Departure (easting change)","formula":"ΔE = dist × sin(azimuth)","calculation_template":"{{dist:f2}} × sin({{az:f2}}°) = {{dep:f2}} ft"},{"step_number":2,"title":"Add to starting easting","result_template":"E = {{e0:f2}} + {{dep:f2}} = {{_answer}} ft"}]'::jsonb, '{"method":"none"}'::jsonb, 'For a NE-quadrant bearing, the departure (change in easting) is dist × sin(bearing angle) = {{dist:f2}} × sin({{az:f2}}°) = {{dep:f2}} ft. Adding to the starting easting {{e0:f2}} gives E = {{_answer}} ft. (The northing would use dist × cos of the same angle.)', 'd2920000-0000-0000-0000-000000000004', ARRAY['land-law','boundary-law','texas','nmsu-sur292','practice']::text[], true, 'seed:nmsu-sur292');

-- ===== Module 5: Module 5: Locating Simultaneous Conveyances =====
