VALUES ('d2920000-0000-0000-0000-000000000006', 'Module 6: Water Rights & Water Boundaries', 'Riparian and littoral rights, navigability, ownership of streambeds, and the location of water boundaries — taught Texas-style around the gradient boundary, the 30-foot navigable-stream statute, the dual coastal datum, and the rule of capture.', 'intermediate', 4, 6, 'published', ARRAY['land-law','boundary-law','texas','nmsu-sur292']::text[], true, 'nmsu-sur292', true, 'approved', 240, 'intermediate')
ON CONFLICT (id) DO UPDATE SET title=EXCLUDED.title, description=EXCLUDED.description, order_index=EXCLUDED.order_index, status='published', is_academic=true, acc_course_id=EXCLUDED.acc_course_id, is_published=true, review_status='approved', tags=EXCLUDED.tags, estimated_hours=EXCLUDED.estimated_hours, updated_at=now();
VALUES ('d2920610-0000-0000-0000-000000000001', 'd2920000-0000-0000-0000-000000000006', 'Riparian vs. Littoral Rights and the Historical Roots of Water Law', '', ARRAY['Riparian rights = flowing water (river/stream); littoral rights = static/tidal water (lake/sea/Gulf).','Riparian/littoral rights attach only to a parcel that actually borders the water — no water boundary, no rights.','The sovereign-owns-the-bed idea runs from Roman law through Spanish Siete Partidas and English common law into the American states via the equal-footing doctrine.','States took bed title at statehood; the U.S. reserved navigable waters when selling public lands — but Texas kept its own public domain and traces title to four sovereigns (Spain, Mexico, Republic, State).']::text[], 1, 35, '[]'::jsonb, '[]'::jsonb, ARRAY['land-law','boundary-law','texas','nmsu-sur292']::text[], 'published', true, 'approved', true, NULL, ARRAY['Define riparian and littoral rights and identify which applies to a given body of water.','Explain how Roman, Spanish, and English common law fed into American — and specifically Texas — water-boundary law.','Apply the equal-footing doctrine and the four-sovereign Texas chain of title to questions of bed ownership.']::text[]);
VALUES ('d2920610-0000-0000-0000-000000000002', 'd2920000-0000-0000-0000-000000000006', 'Navigability and Ownership of Beds: The Texas 30-Foot Statute', '', ARRAY['Federal test: navigable-in-fact for commerce (The Daniel Ball). Texas ALSO uses a statutory test.','Tex. Nat. Res. Code §21.001(3): a stream is navigable if it retains an average bed width of 30 feet from the mouth up — measured bank to bank, not by the water present on a given day.','Navigable stream → State owns the bed (gradient boundary limits private title); non-navigable stream → abutting owners take to the center/thread.','The 1929 Small Bill relinquished the streambed SURFACE to riparian owners but reserved minerals to the State and preserved the public''s water rights.']::text[], 2, 40, '[]'::jsonb, '[]'::jsonb, ARRAY['land-law','boundary-law','texas','nmsu-sur292']::text[], 'published', true, 'approved', true, NULL, ARRAY['Apply the federal commerce test and the Texas statutory 30-foot test of navigability.','State who owns the bed of a navigable vs. a non-navigable stream in Texas.','Explain the curative effect — and the mineral reservation — of the 1929 Small Bill.']::text[]);
VALUES ('d2920610-0000-0000-0000-000000000003', 'd2920000-0000-0000-0000-000000000006', 'The Texas Gradient Boundary on Navigable Streams', '', ARRAY['The gradient boundary is the Texas limit of private title on a navigable stream: a graded line midway up the qualified cut bank, NOT the ordinary high-water mark.','It came from Oklahoma v. Texas (1923, Stiles) and was adopted for Texas public/private ownership in Motl v. Boyd (1926); refined as the mid-height of the lowest qualified bank in Brainard v. State (2000).','Motl v. Boyd defines the bed by the water''s average and mean annual stage, ignoring extreme freshets and droughts.','On non-navigable streams there is no State bed: owners take to the medium filum aquae (centerline/thread/thalweg).']::text[], 3, 40, '[]'::jsonb, '[]'::jsonb, ARRAY['land-law','boundary-law','texas','nmsu-sur292']::text[], 'published', true, 'approved', true, NULL, ARRAY['Define the gradient boundary and the qualified/cut bank.','Trace the development of the method through Oklahoma v. Texas, Motl v. Boyd, and Brainard v. State.','Contrast the gradient boundary with the ordinary high-water mark used in other states, and apply the medium-filum rule on non-navigable streams.']::text[]);
VALUES ('d2920610-0000-0000-0000-000000000004', 'd2920000-0000-0000-0000-000000000006', 'Tidal and Coastal Boundaries: Tides, Datums, and the Dual Standard', '', ARRAY['Tidal datums are 18.6-year-epoch averages; Borax (1935) requires scientific averaging and sets mean high water as the Anglo-American coastal boundary.','MHHW (mean higher high water) averages only the higher daily high tide and lies LANDWARD of MHW.','Texas dual rule (Luttes v. State): Spanish/Mexican grants → MHHW; Republic/State grants → mean high tide (MHW). Trace the sovereign first.','TOBA gives the public an easement over the dry beach to the vegetation line; Severance v. Patterson stops the easement from automatically rolling onto private land after an AVULSIVE event.']::text[], 4, 40, '[]'::jsonb, '[]'::jsonb, ARRAY['land-law','boundary-law','texas','nmsu-sur292']::text[], 'published', true, 'approved', true, NULL, ARRAY['Define the principal tidal datums and the 18.6-year tidal epoch.','Apply the Texas dual coastal rule (Luttes v. State): MHHW for Spanish/Mexican grants, mean high tide for Anglo/Texas grants.','Explain the Texas Open Beaches Act, the rolling easement, and the limit imposed by Severance v. Patterson.']::text[]);
VALUES ('d2920610-0000-0000-0000-000000000005', 'd2920000-0000-0000-0000-000000000006', 'Shoreline Change and Apportionment of New Land', '', ARRAY['Accretion and reliction (gradual gains) go to the upland owner and move the boundary; erosion (gradual loss) moves it landward; avulsion (sudden) FIXES the boundary and changes no title.','The moment of an avulsion fixes ownership; manmade/artificial change does not benefit the owner who caused it.','Newly formed riparian land is divided with equity and justice — water frontage normally controls; ''no geometric theorem governs all cases.''','The proportionate-shoreline method (Johnston v. Jones; BLM Manual) is the federal/majority default: new frontage is split in the same ratio as the old frontage.']::text[], 5, 45, '[]'::jsonb, '[]'::jsonb, ARRAY['land-law','boundary-law','texas','nmsu-sur292']::text[], 'published', true, 'approved', true, NULL, ARRAY['Distinguish accretion, reliction, erosion, and avulsion and their differing effects on title.','Apply the rule that gradual change moves the boundary while avulsion fixes it.','Apportion newly formed riparian land among adjoining owners using the proportionate-shoreline method.']::text[]);
VALUES ('d2920610-0000-0000-0000-000000000006', 'd2920000-0000-0000-0000-000000000006', 'Water USE Law: Surface Water Appropriation vs. Groundwater Rule of Capture', '', ARRAY['Surface water in Texas is State-owned; use requires a TCEQ appropriation permit (prior appropriation), except limited domestic/livestock use.','The 1967 Water Rights Adjudication Act merged riparian claims into the unified appropriation permit system.','Groundwater follows the rule of capture (H&TC Ry. v. East, 1904): pump freely, generally without liability to neighbors.','Edwards Aquifer Authority v. Day (2012): the landowner owns groundwater in place; GCD over-regulation can be a compensable taking.']::text[], 6, 35, '[]'::jsonb, '[]'::jsonb, ARRAY['land-law','boundary-law','texas','nmsu-sur292']::text[], 'published', true, 'approved', true, NULL, ARRAY['Explain that Texas surface water is State-owned and used only by TCEQ appropriation permit.','State the Texas rule of capture for groundwater and the ownership-in-place principle of Edwards Aquifer Authority v. Day.','Distinguish the right to a water BOUNDARY from the right to USE the water.']::text[]);
  'd2920650-0000-0000-0000-000000000001', 'Statutory navigability of a Texas stream from a vara width', 'Statutory navigability of a Texas stream from a vara width', 'Water Boundaries', 'Navigability (30-ft rule)', 'numeric_input', 'easy', 'An original GLO field note reports the average bed width of a stream, cut bank to cut bank, as {{wvrs:f2}} varas. Convert this average width to feet to apply the Texas statutory navigability test of Tex. Nat. Res. Code §21.001(3). (1 vara = 33⅓ in = 2.77778 ft.) What is the average bed width in feet?', 'wvrs*2.7777778', '{"decimals":2,"unit":"ft","tolerance":0.05}', '[{"name":"wvrs","type":"float","min":7,"max":16,"decimals":2}]'::jsonb, '[]'::jsonb, '[{"step_number":1,"title":"Vara-to-foot factor","calculation_template":"1 vara = 33.3333 in ÷ 12 = 2.77778 ft"},{"step_number":2,"title":"Convert width","calculation_template":"{{wvrs:f2}} vrs × 2.77778 ft/vr"},{"step_number":3,"title":"Apply the 30-ft test","result_template":"= {{_answer}} ft; navigable if ≥ 30 ft"}]'::jsonb, '{"method":"none"}'::jsonb, 'Convert varas to feet (× 2.77778): {{wvrs:f2}} vrs = {{_answer}} ft. Under §21.001(3) the stream is statutorily navigable (State-owned bed, gradient boundary) only if this average bed width is at least 30 ft; otherwise it is non-navigable and owners take to the center thread.', 'd2920000-0000-0000-0000-000000000006', ARRAY['land-law','boundary-law','texas','nmsu-sur292','practice']::text[], true, 'seed:nmsu-sur292');
  'd2920650-0000-0000-0000-000000000002', 'Apportioning new shoreline by proportionate-shoreline method', 'Apportioning new shoreline by proportionate-shoreline method', 'Water Boundaries', 'Accretion apportionment', 'numeric_input', 'medium', 'Three riparian owners share one side of a slowly accreting shore. Their ORIGINAL frontages on the old waterline are A = {{fa:f2}} ft, B = {{fb:f2}} ft, and C = {{fc:f2}} ft. Accretion has lengthened the NEW waterline to {{lnew:f2}} ft total. Using the proportionate-shoreline method (new frontage split in the same ratio as old frontage), how many feet of the NEW waterline are allotted to owner B?', '(fb/(fa+fb+fc))*((fa+fb+fc)*growth)', '{"decimals":2,"unit":"ft","tolerance":0.1}', '[{"name":"fa","type":"float","min":120,"max":260,"decimals":2},{"name":"fb","type":"float","min":120,"max":260,"decimals":2},{"name":"fc","type":"float","min":120,"max":260,"decimals":2},{"name":"growth","type":"float","min":1.1,"max":1.45,"decimals":3}]'::jsonb, '[{"name":"ftot","formula":"fa+fb+fc"},{"name":"lnew","formula":"(fa+fb+fc)*growth"}]'::jsonb, '[{"step_number":1,"title":"Total old frontage","calculation_template":"{{fa:f2}} + {{fb:f2}} + {{fc:f2}} = {{ftot:f2}} ft"},{"step_number":2,"title":"B''s proportion","calculation_template":"{{fb:f2}} ÷ {{ftot:f2}}"},{"step_number":3,"title":"Apply to new waterline","result_template":"({{fb:f2}} ÷ {{ftot:f2}}) × {{lnew:f2}} = {{_answer}} ft"}]'::jsonb, '{"method":"none"}'::jsonb, 'The proportionate-shoreline method (Johnston v. Jones; BLM Manual) gives each owner the same share of the NEW waterline as of the OLD. B''s share = (B''s frontage ÷ total old frontage) × new waterline = ({{fb:f2}} ÷ {{ftot:f2}}) × {{lnew:f2}} = {{_answer}} ft.', 'd2920000-0000-0000-0000-000000000006', ARRAY['land-law','boundary-law','texas','nmsu-sur292','practice']::text[], true, 'seed:nmsu-sur292');
  'd2920650-0000-0000-0000-000000000003', 'Area of accreted (riparian) land along a frontage', 'Area of accreted (riparian) land along a frontage', 'Water Boundaries', 'Accretion area', 'numeric_input', 'medium', 'Gradual accretion has built a band of new land in front of a riparian lot. The lot''s water frontage is {{front:f2}} ft and the new alluvion extends an average of {{depth:f2}} ft outward from the old waterline to the new one. Treating the band as frontage × average depth, how many ACRES of accreted land has the riparian owner gained? (1 acre = 43,560 sq ft.)', '(front*depth)/43560', '{"decimals":3,"unit":"ac","tolerance":0.005}', '[{"name":"front","type":"float","min":200,"max":650,"decimals":2},{"name":"depth","type":"float","min":40,"max":160,"decimals":2}]'::jsonb, '[{"name":"area_sf","formula":"front*depth"}]'::jsonb, '[{"step_number":1,"title":"Area in square feet","calculation_template":"{{front:f2}} ft × {{depth:f2}} ft = {{area_sf:f2}} sq ft"},{"step_number":2,"title":"Convert to acres","calculation_template":"{{area_sf:f2}} ÷ 43,560"},{"step_number":3,"title":"Accreted area","result_template":"= {{_answer}} acres"}]'::jsonb, '{"method":"none"}'::jsonb, 'Accretion gradually added land that belongs to the upland owner. Area = frontage × average accretion depth = {{front:f2}} × {{depth:f2}} = {{area_sf:f2}} sq ft = {{_answer}} acres (÷ 43,560).', 'd2920000-0000-0000-0000-000000000006', ARRAY['land-law','boundary-law','texas','nmsu-sur292','practice']::text[], true, 'seed:nmsu-sur292');

-- ===== Module 7: Module 7: Creation of Metes and Bounds Descriptions =====
