VALUES ('d2920000-0000-0000-0000-000000000007', 'Module 7: Creation of Metes and Bounds Descriptions', 'How a legally sufficient metes-and-bounds land description is built and read — caption, point of beginning, the body of courses (bearings and distances), calls for monuments, closure, area, and certification — with bearings/azimuths, latitude/departure, and closure math, made Texas-specific (GLO original-survey/abstract ties, vara-based historic field notes, and the TBPELS standards in 22 TAC Ch. 138).', 'intermediate', 4.5, 7, 'published', ARRAY['land-law','boundary-law','texas','nmsu-sur292']::text[], true, 'nmsu-sur292', true, 'approved', 270, 'intermediate')
ON CONFLICT (id) DO UPDATE SET title=EXCLUDED.title, description=EXCLUDED.description, order_index=EXCLUDED.order_index, status='published', is_academic=true, acc_course_id=EXCLUDED.acc_course_id, is_published=true, review_status='approved', tags=EXCLUDED.tags, estimated_hours=EXCLUDED.estimated_hours, updated_at=now();
VALUES ('d2920710-0000-0000-0000-000000000001', 'd2920000-0000-0000-0000-000000000007', 'Metes, Bounds, and the Anatomy of a Description', '', ARRAY['A description must make intent clear, identify and locate one unique parcel, fix its size/shape/position, and not create gaps or overlaps — or the conveyance may be void.','Metes are measures (bearings and distances); bounds are adjoiners. Most modern descriptions combine the two.','Every description has a caption, a body (POC → POB → courses → closing call), an area statement, optional clauses, a basis of bearing, and certification.','Words alone can create a binding boundary; the lines and corners of the original survey control its location, interpreted as of the date written.']::text[], 1, 35, '[]'::jsonb, '[]'::jsonb, ARRAY['land-law','boundary-law','texas','nmsu-sur292']::text[], 'published', true, 'approved', true, NULL, ARRAY['Distinguish metes from bounds and name the principal types of land description.','Identify the parts of a written description: caption, body, closing, area, and certification.','State the foundational principles that govern how a description creates a boundary.']::text[]);
VALUES ('d2920710-0000-0000-0000-000000000002', 'd2920000-0000-0000-0000-000000000007', 'The Caption, the Point of Beginning, and Texas Ties to the GLO Survey', '', ARRAY['The caption locates and limits the parcel; the body controls a conflicting caption, but a limiting caption can cap what the body conveys.','A POC is a reliably found point that may not be a parcel corner; the POB is the one true corner where the perimeter starts. Use “Commencing at” then “Point of Beginning.”','Texas captions key to the original GLO survey + abstract number, not Section/Township/Range — Texas has no PLSS grid.','Tie the POB and a controlling corner to the original survey and state the basis of bearing (today usually Texas State Plane / NAD83), per 22 TAC §138.91.']::text[], 2, 35, '[]'::jsonb, '[]'::jsonb, ARRAY['land-law','boundary-law','texas','nmsu-sur292']::text[], 'published', true, 'approved', true, NULL, ARRAY['Write a caption that locates and limits a parcel, using Texas GLO survey/abstract conventions.','Distinguish a point of commencement (POC) from a point of beginning (POB) and tie a parcel to known control.','State the Texas requirement to anchor a description to an original land-grant survey and abstract number.']::text[]);
VALUES ('d2920710-0000-0000-0000-000000000003', 'd2920000-0000-0000-0000-000000000007', 'Bearings, Azimuths, and the Body of Courses', '', ARRAY['A quadrant bearing is N/S __° E/W (≤ 90°); an azimuth is clockwise from north 0–360°. Convert by quadrant; the back course is azimuth ± 180° and flips both bearing letters.','Latitude = D·cosβ (± N/S) and Departure = D·sinβ (± E/W) resolve a course into N–S and E–W components and let you carry coordinates around the parcel.','The body runs the calls in order, clockwise or counter-clockwise, each starting “thence,” with a stated basis of bearing.','Bearings/distances are “finger pointings” to the controlling monuments; “more or less” keeps recited numbers from outranking a found monument.']::text[], 3, 45, '[]'::jsonb, '[]'::jsonb, ARRAY['land-law','boundary-law','texas','nmsu-sur292']::text[], 'published', true, 'approved', true, NULL, ARRAY['Read and write a quadrant bearing and convert between a bearing and an azimuth (and the back course).','Compute the latitude and departure of a course from its bearing and distance.','Order and phrase the calls in the body so they run cleanly around the parcel.']::text[]);
VALUES ('d2920710-0000-0000-0000-000000000004', 'd2920000-0000-0000-0000-000000000007', 'Closure, Sufficiency, and Common Defects', '', ARRAY['Sum the latitudes and departures; the linear misclosure = √(ΣLat² + ΣDep²). A description that will not close (no gap/overlap) is defective.','Sufficiency = close + locatable + unambiguous, all required by 22 TAC §138.91; closure tolerances live in §138.83 and the TSPS Manual.','The modern tendency favors upholding a deed and using extrinsic evidence to locate (not rewrite) ambiguous lands.','When calls conflict, apply the dignity of calls (natural → artificial → adjoinder → course → distance → area), subordinate to intent and the original surveyor''s footsteps.']::text[], 4, 45, '[]'::jsonb, '[]'::jsonb, ARRAY['land-law','boundary-law','texas','nmsu-sur292']::text[], 'published', true, 'approved', true, NULL, ARRAY['Compute the linear misclosure of a traverse from the sums of latitudes and departures.','State the three sufficiency requirements: a description must close, be locatable, and be unambiguous.','Recognize common defects and apply the dignity of calls to evaluate a description.']::text[]);
VALUES ('d2920710-0000-0000-0000-000000000005', 'd2920000-0000-0000-0000-000000000007', 'Texas Conventions: Varas, the GLO, and Putting a Description Together', '', ARRAY['Texas field notes in varas convert at 1 vara = 2.7778 ft (feet × 0.36 = varas); use the statutory 33⅓-in vara, never a foreign value, and reconcile the historic bearing basis.','The GLO holds the original grant records a retracing surveyor must consult; state-land originals require an LSLS, and patents sever land from the sovereign.','Only an RPLS/LSLS may prepare and seal a Texas description, under 22 TAC Ch. 138 Subch. E (§§138.83, .87, .91) — not the repealed §663.','Finish with the area “more or less,” the right EXCEPTING/RESERVING/SUBJECT TO/TOGETHER WITH clauses, a call for the survey, the basis of bearing, and certification.']::text[], 5, 40, '[]'::jsonb, '[]'::jsonb, ARRAY['land-law','boundary-law','texas','nmsu-sur292']::text[], 'published', true, 'approved', true, NULL, ARRAY['Convert vara-based historic field notes to feet and explain why the original units govern.','Describe the role of the GLO and the credentials and standards that govern Texas descriptions.','Assemble a complete, compliant Texas metes-and-bounds description and add the proper clauses and certification.']::text[]);
  'd2920750-0000-0000-0000-000000000001', 'Bearing to azimuth and back-azimuth', 'Bearing to azimuth and back-azimuth', 'Boundary Law — Metes and Bounds', 'Bearings and Azimuths', 'numeric_input', 'easy', 'A deed course is recited as {{quad}} {{ang}} degrees {{min}} minutes (a bearing of {{ang}}°{{min}}'' measured from the {{ns}} meridian toward the {{ew}}). Express this course as an AZIMUTH measured clockwise from north, in decimal degrees.', '[base, 180-base, 180+base, 360-base][q]', '{"decimals":2,"unit":"degrees","tolerance":0.02}', '[{"name":"q","type":"integer","min":0,"max":3},{"name":"ang","type":"integer","min":5,"max":80},{"name":"min","type":"choice","choices":["00","15","30","45"]}]'::jsonb, '[{"name":"quad","formula":"[''N'',''S'',''S'',''N''][q] + '' ___ '' + [''E'',''E'',''W'',''W''][q]"},{"name":"ns","formula":"[''north'',''south'',''south'',''north''][q]"},{"name":"ew","formula":"[''east'',''east'',''west'',''west''][q]"},{"name":"base","formula":"ang + (min==''00''?0:(min==''15''?0.25:(min==''30''?0.5:0.75)))"}]'::jsonb, '[{"step_number":1,"title":"Identify the quadrant","calculation_template":"Bearing is {{quad}} (toward the {{ew}} from the {{ns}})"},{"step_number":2,"title":"Apply the quadrant rule","calculation_template":"NE: Az=β; SE: Az=180−β; SW: Az=180+β; NW: Az=360−β (here β={{base:f2}}°)"},{"step_number":3,"title":"Compute the azimuth","result_template":"Azimuth = {{_answer}} degrees"}]'::jsonb, '{"method":"none"}'::jsonb, 'Convert the quadrant bearing {{quad}} ({{base:f2}}°) to azimuth using the rule for its quadrant. The azimuth is {{_answer}}°. (Its back-azimuth would be this ± 180°.)', 'd2920000-0000-0000-0000-000000000007', ARRAY['land-law','boundary-law','texas','nmsu-sur292','practice']::text[], true, 'seed:nmsu-sur292');
  'd2920750-0000-0000-0000-000000000002', 'Latitude or departure of a single course', 'Latitude or departure of a single course', 'Boundary Law — Metes and Bounds', 'Latitude and Departure', 'numeric_input', 'medium', 'A course bears {{nsword}} {{ang}} degrees {{ewword}} for a distance of {{dist:f2}} feet. Compute the magnitude of its {{which}} (the {{axis}} component), in feet.', 'comp==0 ? dist*cos(toRad(ang)) : dist*sin(toRad(ang))', '{"decimals":2,"unit":"ft","tolerance":0.05}', '[{"name":"ns","type":"integer","min":0,"max":1},{"name":"ew","type":"integer","min":0,"max":1},{"name":"ang","type":"integer","min":10,"max":80},{"name":"dist","type":"float","min":120,"max":600,"decimals":2},{"name":"comp","type":"integer","min":0,"max":1}]'::jsonb, '[{"name":"nsword","formula":"ns==0?''North'':''South''"},{"name":"ewword","formula":"ew==0?''East'':''West''"},{"name":"which","formula":"comp==0?''LATITUDE'':''DEPARTURE''"},{"name":"axis","formula":"comp==0?''north-south'':''east-west''"}]'::jsonb, '[{"step_number":1,"title":"Pick the right trig function","calculation_template":"Latitude = D·cosβ (N–S); Departure = D·sinβ (E–W). Here we need the {{which}}."},{"step_number":2,"title":"Substitute","calculation_template":"{{dist:f2}} × ({{which}} uses cos for latitude, sin for departure) of {{ang}}°"},{"step_number":3,"title":"Result","result_template":"{{which}} magnitude = {{_answer}} ft"}]'::jsonb, '{"method":"none"}'::jsonb, 'Resolve the course into components: latitude = D·cosβ and departure = D·sinβ, with β = {{ang}}° and D = {{dist:f2}} ft. The requested {{which}} has magnitude {{_answer}} ft. Its sign would be {{nsword}}/{{ewword}} depending on the quadrant.', 'd2920000-0000-0000-0000-000000000007', ARRAY['land-law','boundary-law','texas','nmsu-sur292','practice']::text[], true, 'seed:nmsu-sur292');
  'd2920750-0000-0000-0000-000000000003', 'Linear misclosure of a traverse', 'Linear misclosure of a traverse', 'Boundary Law — Metes and Bounds', 'Closure', 'numeric_input', 'medium', 'After summing the latitudes and departures of all courses in a closed traverse, a surveyor finds a closure in latitude of ΣLat = {{sumLat:f2}} feet and a closure in departure of ΣDep = {{sumDep:f2}} feet. Compute the linear misclosure (the straight-line gap back to the point of beginning), in feet.', 'hypot(sumLat, sumDep)', '{"decimals":3,"unit":"ft","tolerance":0.01}', '[{"name":"sumLat","type":"float","min":-0.9,"max":0.9,"decimals":2},{"name":"sumDep","type":"float","min":-0.9,"max":0.9,"decimals":2}]'::jsonb, '[]'::jsonb, '[{"step_number":1,"title":"State the formula","formula":"misclosure = √(ΣLat² + ΣDep²)","calculation_template":"ΣLat = {{sumLat:f2}} ft, ΣDep = {{sumDep:f2}} ft"},{"step_number":2,"title":"Square and add","calculation_template":"{{sumLat:f2}}² + {{sumDep:f2}}²"},{"step_number":3,"title":"Take the square root","result_template":"misclosure = {{_answer}} ft"}]'::jsonb, '{"method":"none"}'::jsonb, 'The linear misclosure is the hypotenuse of the latitude and departure closures: √({{sumLat:f2}}² + {{sumDep:f2}}²) = {{_answer}} ft. In a perfect figure both sums (and the misclosure) would be zero.', 'd2920000-0000-0000-0000-000000000007', ARRAY['land-law','boundary-law','texas','nmsu-sur292','practice']::text[], true, 'seed:nmsu-sur292');
  'd2920750-0000-0000-0000-000000000004', 'Area of a triangular parcel in acres', 'Area of a triangular parcel in acres', 'Boundary Law — Metes and Bounds', 'Area', 'numeric_input', 'medium', 'A triangular parcel has a base of {{base:f2}} feet along a road and a perpendicular height (depth) of {{height:f2}} feet. Compute its area in ACRES (1 acre = 43,560 square feet).', '(base*height/2)/43560', '{"decimals":3,"unit":"acres","tolerance":0.01}', '[{"name":"base","type":"float","min":200,"max":900,"decimals":2},{"name":"height","type":"float","min":150,"max":700,"decimals":2}]'::jsonb, '[{"name":"sqft","formula":"base*height/2"}]'::jsonb, '[{"step_number":1,"title":"Triangle area in square feet","formula":"A = (base × height) / 2","calculation_template":"({{base:f2}} × {{height:f2}}) / 2 = {{sqft:f2}} sq ft"},{"step_number":2,"title":"Convert to acres","result_template":"{{sqft:f2}} ÷ 43,560 = {{_answer}} acres"}]'::jsonb, '{"method":"none"}'::jsonb, 'A triangle''s area is (base × height) / 2 = ({{base:f2}} × {{height:f2}})/2 = {{sqft:f2}} sq ft. Dividing by 43,560 sq ft/acre gives {{_answer}} acres (which the description would state “more or less”).', 'd2920000-0000-0000-0000-000000000007', ARRAY['land-law','boundary-law','texas','nmsu-sur292','practice']::text[], true, 'seed:nmsu-sur292');

-- Ensure a default learning_module XP value exists (idempotent).
